That makes the platitudes
harder to bear.

504
00:36:31,637 --> 00:36:33,268
They do, people wanna help.

505
00:36:33,268 --> 00:36:36,373
All right? I wanna help you,
but I don't know what to do.

506
00:36:36,373 --> 00:36:38,577
I don't need the company line
right now, okay?

507
00:36:41,078 --> 00:36:42,485
Okay.

508
00:36:43,254 --> 00:36:46,262
Jesus. Listen to me.

509
00:36:46,262 --> 00:36:49,328
All I see is the dark side of everything.

510
00:36:50,678 --> 00:36:52,247
Poor Ruby.

511
00:36:52,247 --> 00:36:54,325
I kill her joy.

512
00:36:54,325 --> 00:36:57,397
Look at her sad, discouraged face.

513
00:36:57,397 --> 00:36:58,706
I don't know what to say.

514
00:37:00,885 --> 00:37:04,399
How about,
"Shit, call in the professionals"?

515
00:37:14,998 --> 00:37:18,228
So I guess this is the Freud part,
where I don't say anything...

516
00:37:18,228 --> 00:37:21,327
...and you don't say anything.
All of a sudden, it's:

517
00:37:21,589 --> 00:37:24,688
"Obviously, you wish to sleep
with your father."

518
00:37:25,621 --> 00:37:28,630
So I'm to take it you don't wish to
sleep with your father?

519
00:37:28,630 --> 00:37:29,972
No.

520
00:37:32,150 --> 00:37:35,085
And I don't wanna talk
about my childhood either.

521
00:37:37,430 --> 00:37:39,317
I don't know why I'm here.

522
00:37:40,820 --> 00:37:42,675
Why might you be here?

523
00:37:45,621 --> 00:37:47,377
I can't write.

524
00:37:48,982 --> 00:37:50,836
And what do you write about?

525
00:37:51,798 --> 00:37:55,350
I write stories, poems, articles.

526
00:37:55,350 --> 00:37:57,936
I'm here on a journalism scholarship.

527
00:38:00,982 --> 00:38:03,828
I've been writing forever. I have to.

528
00:38:04,789 --> 00:38:07,342
How long has it been
since you stopped writing?

529
00:38:08,917 --> 00:38:10,543
About a month.

530
00:38:11,605 --> 00:38:14,198
Do you remember
the first thing you wrote?

531
00:38:14,198 --> 00:38:15,798
A poem.

532
00:38:15,798 --> 00:38:17,870
A poem. About what?

533
00:38:18,166 --> 00:38:19,627
My dad.

534
00:38:20,246 --> 00:38:22,070
Can you remember anything it said?

535
00:38:22,070 --> 00:38:24,526
I told you, I don't wanna
talk about my childhood.

536
00:38:28,053 --> 00:38:31,221
I just... I feel so stupid,
sitting in therapy.

537
00:38:31,221 --> 00:38:33,558
People have much harder
childhoods than mine.

538
00:38:33,558 --> 00:38:36,307
We're not talking about others.
We're talking about you.

539
00:38:36,790 --> 00:38:38,869
I'll give her that much.

540
00:38:38,869 --> 00:38:40,779
I'm the problem.

541
00:38:43,126 --> 00:38:45,622
I worry about being in therapy.

542
00:38:45,622 --> 00:38:48,470
I worry about not being in therapy.

543
00:38:48,470 --> 00:38:51,665
I even worry I'm not entertaining
enough for Dr. Sterling.

544
00:38:51,989 --> 00:38:55,381
I just keep thinking that
if I could just be normal...

545
00:38:55,381 --> 00:38:59,349
...if I could just get out of bed in the
morning, everything would be okay.

546
00:38:59,349 --> 00:39:01,172
Well, what do you think normal is?

547
00:39:03,670 --> 00:39:07,413
Most people, they cut themselves,
they put a Band-Aid on, keep going.

548
00:39:07,734 --> 00:39:08,912
And what do you do?

549
00:39:09,654 --> 00:39:10,931
I just keep bleeding.

550
00:39:11,543 --> 00:39:15,157
So you think being normal is having
a wound, putting a patch on it...

551
00:39:15,157 --> 00:39:16,618
...then go on with your life?

552
00:39:17,589 --> 00:39:19,083
Isn't that what functioning is?

553
00:39:19,925 --> 00:39:22,006
Isn't that what living is?

554
00:39:22,006 --> 00:39:24,949
You know, you keep going,
no matter what happens to you.

555
00:39:24,949 --> 00:39:26,738
Is that the way you wanna live?

556
00:39:52,854 --> 00:39:54,447
Mom.

557
00:39:56,407 --> 00:39:58,578
Oh, come on, now, honey.

558
00:39:58,871 --> 00:40:02,764
Why don't you tie up your hair
anymore? Your face is so pretty.

559
00:40:06,133 --> 00:40:07,988
Here they are.

560
00:40:14,262 --> 00:40:15,920
Come on, now, Lizzie.

561
00:40:22,167 --> 00:40:24,816
Hi, honey!

562
00:40:28,309 --> 00:40:30,381
Is she home yet?

563
00:40:38,967 --> 00:40:43,058
I need someone to shut off my brain
and turn on my heart.

564
00:40:43,734 --> 00:40:48,565
Well, I have long brown hair,
dark eyes.

565
00:40:48,565 --> 00:40:51,317
You probably meet tons of
girls in the men's bathroom.

566
00:40:51,317 --> 00:40:54,700
Oh, yeah, the Ecstasy goddess.

567
00:40:55,286 --> 00:40:58,230
Yes, I can't believe
you remember that.

568
00:40:58,230 --> 00:40:59,637
Lizzie.

569
00:41:02,711 --> 00:41:04,620
Can you hang on a sec?

570
00:41:05,495 --> 00:41:07,607
Grandma and Grandpa are here.

571
00:41:07,607 --> 00:41:08,916
Yes, I heard.

572
00:41:10,325 --> 00:41:15,628
You know, the only reason I threw a
birthday party was to make you happy.

573
00:41:17,269 --> 00:41:20,278
I don't understand how you can
treat me like this.

574
00:41:20,278 --> 00:41:21,904
Can I have some privacy, please?

575
00:41:31,703 --> 00:41:33,392
That was my mother.

576
00:41:33,781 --> 00:41:37,174
It's my birthday.
She's throwing this big party for me.

577
00:41:37,174 --> 00:41:38,805
Cool.

578
00:41:38,805 --> 00:41:41,391
Well, no, actually, it's not.

579
00:41:41,718 --> 00:41:44,534
It's just me and my mother
and my grandparents.

580
00:41:44,534 --> 00:41:46,192
I haven't even been out there yet.

581
00:41:46,154 --> 00:41:47,943
Aren't they missing you?

582
00:41:48,266 --> 00:41:50,474
Well, now you sound like
a nice Jewish boy.

583
00:41:50,474 --> 00:41:53,343
Well, I might, if I was Jewish.

584
00:41:54,409 --> 00:41:56,711
I just wanted to call and say hi.

585
00:41:58,026 --> 00:42:00,330
Let's meet up when
you get back to school.

586
00:42:00,330 --> 00:42:02,442
Okay, that'd be great.

587
00:42:02,442 --> 00:42:05,639
Hey, happy birthday.

588
00:42:07,691 --> 00:42:09,185
Thank you.

589
00:42:11,563 --> 00:42:13,450
Rafe didn't seem to realize...

590
00:42:13,450 --> 00:42:16,353
...he'd just been appointed
to save my life.

591
00:42:18,891 --> 00:42:21,418
Rolling Stone magazine.

592
00:42:21,418 --> 00:42:24,426
It's the music magazine.

593
00:42:24,426 --> 00:42:27,691
That's wonderful, honey.

594
00:42:27,691 --> 00:42:32,394
They want her to work for them. Yeah.
Paid work for Rolling Stone.

595
00:42:32,939 --> 00:42:34,313
They'll pay her?

596
00:42:40,875 --> 00:42:44,105
I think she was up writing
late last night.

597
00:42:45,035 --> 00:42:46,977
Were you up writing late last night?

598
00:42:47,755 --> 00:42:49,544
I haven't written anything in months.

599
00:42:50,795 --> 00:42:53,164
She's always working on something.

600
00:42:53,164 --> 00:42:55,276
She just doesn't like to talk about it.

601
00:42:55,276 --> 00:42:57,000
Like you've ever read any of it.

602
00:43:02,764 --> 00:43:04,812
Lizzie, this isn't very nice.

603
00:43:04,812 --> 00:43:06,373
You want one?

604
00:43:15,883 --> 00:43:18,699
What's wrong with her?

605
00:43:19,339 --> 00:43:22,124
Nothing. Ma, nothing's wrong with her.

606
00:43:22,124 --> 00:43:24,716
- She's drunk.
- Of course I'm drunk.

607
00:43:24,716 --> 00:43:28,044
- She's just tired.
- She's as skinny as a ghost.

608
00:43:28,044 --> 00:43:30,248
She's overtired.
They work so hard up there.

609
00:43:31,756 --> 00:43:33,797
- Lizzie.
- Is she on drugs?

610
00:43:34,637 --> 00:43:37,069
- I wish I was on drugs.
- Lizzie.

611
00:43:37,069 --> 00:43:38,957
- Did she say that she...?
- No, Ma.

612
00:43:38,957 --> 00:43:41,388
It's okay. Everything is okay.

613
00:43:41,388 --> 00:43:44,493
Mom, believe me,
if I was on drugs, I'd tell you.

614
00:43:44,493 --> 00:43:47,469
People don't behave this way
if they're not on drugs.

615
00:43:47,469 --> 00:43:49,771
I fucking do.

616
00:44:00,557 --> 00:44:02,891
I'm so sorry, Mama.

617
00:44:12,237 --> 00:44:15,597
I dream about all the things
I wish I'd said.

618
00:44:15,597 --> 00:44:18,606
The opposite of what
came out of my mouth.

619
00:44:18,606 --> 00:44:22,061
I wish I'd said,
"Mom, please forgive me.

620
00:44:22,061 --> 00:44:24,110
Please help me.

621
00:44:24,110 --> 00:44:27,274
I know I have no right
to behave this way."

622
00:44:40,142 --> 00:44:42,126
- Hello.
- Hey.

623
00:44:42,126 --> 00:44:45,199
- Hi.
- How' my birthday girl?

624
00:44:45,199 --> 00:44:47,502
You're late. You're a day late.

625
00:44:47,502 --> 00:44:49,707
What can I say, you know how it is.

626
00:44:49,967 --> 00:44:53,871
Anyway, I thought I'd have to be
dealing with your secretary by now.

627
00:44:53,871 --> 00:44:57,166
You're such a bigshot journalist,
writing for Rolling Stone.

628
00:44:57,166 --> 00:44:59,054
- Did you read it?
- You know...

629
00:44:59,054 --> 00:45:01,355
...remember this,
they're lucky to have you.

630
00:45:02,254 --> 00:45:05,039
These guys, they're smart.
They're really smart.

631
00:45:05,039 --> 00:45:07,599
They know what they're doing.
They can see talent.

632
00:45:07,599 --> 00:45:10,575
I'm probably gonna get assignments
all over the country...

633
00:45:10,575 --> 00:45:12,591
...so I could maybe come visit you.

634
00:45:12,591 --> 00:45:14,500
Who are you talking to, Lizzie?

635
00:45:16,110 --> 00:45:18,511
- It's no one.
- Who is it?

636
00:45:18,511 --> 00:45:20,335
- It's no one.
- Don't listen to her.

637
00:45:20,335 --> 00:45:21,742
Please, Mom.

638
00:45:23,087 --> 00:45:25,328
Look at you, the two of you.

639
00:45:25,328 --> 00:45:27,631
- Go on, you're so in love with him.
- Mom.

640
00:45:27,631 --> 00:45:29,871
Can you hear that?
Hear why I don't call?

641
00:45:29,871 --> 00:45:31,535
Where was he your childhood?

642
00:45:31,535 --> 00:45:33,543
- Where...?
- Stop it! Just stop it!

643
00:45:35,984 --> 00:45:38,544
I just wanted to talk to him!

644
00:45:38,544 --> 00:45:41,032
You know, Lizzie,
I'm at the end of my rope.

645
00:45:43,760 --> 00:45:47,535
I've been working extra hours.
I never go out.

646
00:45:47,919 --> 00:45:51,782
I never buy clothes.
I spend all our money on your therapy.

647
00:45:53,008 --> 00:45:55,309
All our money? Daddy pays, Mom.

648
00:45:55,631 --> 00:45:57,518
You think he pays?

649
00:45:58,671 --> 00:46:00,843
You think he's paying?

650
00:46:01,231 --> 00:46:04,272
He doesn't pay one cent.

651
00:46:04,272 --> 00:46:08,133
Not one single red cent!

652
00:46:09,040 --> 00:46:10,895
That's not true.

653
00:46:11,216 --> 00:46:14,544
Oh, you want me to show you?
Huh? You wanna see?

654
00:46:14,544 --> 00:46:19,089
You want to see how much I'm paying,
still paying...

655
00:46:19,089 --> 00:46:21,744
...on your last term bill? Huh?

656
00:46:21,744 --> 00:46:24,592
Here. Here, look at these.
Look at these.

657
00:46:24,592 --> 00:46:27,569
- There, look at that, Lizzie.
- I'm sorry, Mom.

658
00:46:27,569 --> 00:46:31,912
You wanna see how much
I'm paying this Dr. Sterling?

659
00:46:32,209 --> 00:46:33,554
I'm sorry.

660
00:46:33,554 --> 00:46:35,953
No, you're not gonna
talk your way out of this.

661
00:46:35,953 --> 00:46:38,703
Ask her who pays her!

662
00:46:41,330 --> 00:46:45,265
You know, it's my fault,
for spoiling you the way I did.

663
00:46:45,265 --> 00:46:49,617
I kill myself to get you to Harvard, and
you come back looking like a zombie.

664
00:46:49,617 --> 00:46:52,334
I know. I'm sorry.

665
00:46:53,265 --> 00:46:54,727
I'm so...

666
00:46:55,473 --> 00:46:57,448
Why won't he?

667
00:46:59,185 --> 00:47:02,032
- Why won't he?
- I know. I know, honey. I know.

668
00:47:03,601 --> 00:47:07,506
I hate myself,
and I hate the things I do.

669
00:47:07,506 --> 00:47:10,354
Lizzie, it's all right. It's all right.

670
00:47:13,810 --> 00:47:16,046
It's awful. It's so awful.

671
00:47:18,385 --> 00:47:21,459
And I hurt the people who love me.

672
00:47:21,459 --> 00:47:24,208
But when he calls...

673
00:47:30,578 --> 00:47:32,520
My God, a party?

674
00:47:32,915 --> 00:47:35,947
And your stupid pear tart!

675
00:47:43,058 --> 00:47:44,562
Why do you do this, Lizzie?

676
00:47:44,562 --> 00:47:48,206
Because I'm not
your goddamn monkey!

677
00:47:52,627 --> 00:47:56,521
I'm sorry, Mom, I didn't mean it.
I'm sorry.

678
00:47:57,139 --> 00:47:59,081
I didn't mean it.

679
00:48:00,530 --> 00:48:02,319
I'm sorry.

680
00:48:10,675 --> 00:48:13,010
She threw the party for herself?

681
00:48:14,227 --> 00:48:15,795
No, I guess for Grandma.

682
00:48:15,795 --> 00:48:18,032
Why would she want to do that?

683
00:48:20,916 --> 00:48:23,566
To show her what
a good little girl she was.

684
00:48:24,404 --> 00:48:26,291
That must really hurt.

685
00:48:27,316 --> 00:48:31,571
Look at her.
This isn't a breakthrough, darling.

686
00:48:32,052 --> 00:48:35,281
My mom pays $ 100 an hour for this.

687
00:48:36,563 --> 00:48:41,748
This is the same bullshit. Insight time.
It's like that stuff with that guy Rafe.

688
00:48:41,748 --> 00:48:44,884
I don't have to be Freud to know
I have a fear of rejection.

689
00:48:44,884 --> 00:48:47,700
And I know where it comes from.
I know it's from my dad.

690
00:48:48,180 --> 00:48:50,612
But it doesn't change anything.

691
00:48:50,612 --> 00:48:53,514
- I still can't go out with him.
- Why not?

692
00:48:54,004 --> 00:48:55,466
I just told you.

693
00:48:58,036 --> 00:49:00,404
You didn't tell me
anything about Rafe.

694
00:49:00,885 --> 00:49:03,568
Has he ever given you reason
to believe he'd reject you?

695
00:49:12,885 --> 00:49:15,024
Do not show him how crazy you are.

696
00:49:16,468 --> 00:49:18,709
- A monkey?
- Called Percy.

697
00:49:18,709 --> 00:49:20,341
I know, it beats me.

698
00:49:20,341 --> 00:49:22,996
- She needed someone to talk to.
- Well, she had you.

699
00:49:22,996 --> 00:49:24,523
No, no, this was before.

700
00:49:24,853 --> 00:49:27,242
- Are you listening?
- God, yes.

701
00:49:27,573 --> 00:49:28,817
I'm not boring you?

702
00:49:29,205 --> 00:49:31,732
Please, Lizzie.
I met you in a men's room.

703
00:49:31,732 --> 00:49:34,962
- You're anything but boring.
- What am I?

704
00:49:36,822 --> 00:49:38,578
Scary.

705
00:49:40,054 --> 00:49:42,443
So are we gonna go to this gig?

706
00:49:44,117 --> 00:49:45,611
I'm not sure.

707
00:49:46,582 --> 00:49:48,438
I don't really know where it is.

708
00:49:48,438 --> 00:49:51,472
You came to see a gig,
and you don't know where it is?

709
00:49:52,054 --> 00:49:55,218
I said I came to see the gig...

710
00:49:58,070 --> 00:49:59,728
You know.

711
00:50:00,598 --> 00:50:04,374
- What?
- Okay, now you're just being cruel.

712
00:50:04,374 --> 00:50:05,942
No, no, you said...

713
00:50:05,942 --> 00:50:09,652
I said I came to see the gig...

714
00:50:10,774 --> 00:50:13,360
...but I came to see you.

715
00:50:33,079 --> 00:50:36,178
Waiting, waiting, waiting.

716
00:50:37,655 --> 00:50:40,502
Waiting for him to make the move.

717
00:50:43,511 --> 00:50:48,269
Doesn't he know?
He' gotta be my salvation.

718
00:50:56,631 --> 00:50:58,776
It' lovely that he' caring...

719
00:50:58,776 --> 00:51:01,843
...compassionate
and politically correct.

720
00:51:02,360 --> 00:51:04,567
But I need him to kiss me.

721
00:51:04,567 --> 00:51:06,390
Right now.

722
00:51:50,841 --> 00:51:52,750
Ruby!

723
00:51:53,498 --> 00:51:55,254
Ruby.

724
00:52:00,505 --> 00:52:01,716
Hey.

725
00:52:01,977 --> 00:52:03,668
Hey.

726
00:52:03,928 --> 00:52:07,573
I didn't know you'd moved rooms.
I thought you were still in here.

727
00:52:09,626 --> 00:52:12,974
Ruby was telling me about
those articles you're planning to write.

728
00:52:14,521 --> 00:52:17,140
That stuff's always
been easy for me.

729
00:52:21,370 --> 00:52:23,929
Dr. Sterling must have called him.

730
00:52:23,929 --> 00:52:26,230
Why else would he be here?

731
00:52:26,713 --> 00:52:29,786
Probably to see how dire
the situation is.

732
00:52:29,786 --> 00:52:32,437
See if his little girl can
get through the day still.

733
00:52:33,178 --> 00:52:34,836
Or...

734
00:52:35,291 --> 00:52:38,257
...maybe he really did finally miss me.

735
00:52:39,226 --> 00:52:40,436
My girl.

736
00:52:43,386 --> 00:52:45,466
Dad, you know those medical bills?

737
00:52:45,466 --> 00:52:47,888
The ones for the psychiatric
treatment?

738
00:52:49,787 --> 00:52:51,867
They keep sending them to Mom.

739
00:52:51,867 --> 00:52:54,485
So I guess you haven't paid.

740
00:52:54,875 --> 00:52:58,233
- I can't believe you're asking me this.
- Oh, you have paid?

741
00:52:58,233 --> 00:53:00,251
You're all cold and distant.

742
00:53:00,251 --> 00:53:02,107
And... And...

743
00:53:02,107 --> 00:53:04,730
And now you're asking me what?

744
00:53:04,730 --> 00:53:06,202
What are you talking about?

745
00:53:06,202 --> 00:53:09,851
- If you don't know...
- No. No, I don't know.

746
00:53:09,851 --> 00:53:13,531
- You made a promise.
- You haven't written me.

747
00:53:13,531 --> 00:53:15,579
You never call me.

748
00:53:15,579 --> 00:53:17,787
It's like I don't even exist.

749
00:53:17,787 --> 00:53:22,267
- Who do you think you're talking to?
- I even come and visit you.

750
00:53:22,267 --> 00:53:24,123
- Fuck you!
- You watch that language!

751
00:53:24,123 --> 00:53:26,587
- Is that a way to talk to your father?
- Listen.

752
00:53:26,587 --> 00:53:30,236
You're the one who left. You're the one
who walked away for four years.

753
